Be aware these are rough jupyter notebooks I (Gary Pavlis) used for 
testing the mspass multichannel cross-correlation module in MsPASS. 
The two key elements of that module are MCXcorPrepP and 
align_and_stack.  Together they can be treated as an automated 
version of something I worked on more than a decade ago calle "dbxcor"
that is part of Antelope.   

These are rough but here is what they do:

MCXcor_Data_Preparation.ipynb
As the name suggests this shows what I had to do to create a test data 
on which I could run the code.   It is not reproducible because it depends 
upon a collection of miniseed data I had spinning at the time I was doing 
that testing. 

MCcorProcessing.ipynb 
This is an example workflow showing how to run the code after the data
set is prepared with something comparable to above. For reasons I don't 
recall the graphics are empty.  Use this notebook with caution as it 
may contain errors. I'm posting it for guidance only.

sidebar.ipynb
This is random bunch of stuff I include for two reasons.  First, it contains 
some useful constructs to help understand what the multichannel does and 
the metadata it creates and requires.   Second, it is a good example for 
anyone using MsPASS of something I find is almost always required when 
using MsPASS.   I use sidebar as a way to validate intermediat results 
without having to color my actual run script with baggage that may not 
be required and which is not necessarily transportable.   Be ESPECIALLY way
that you MUST NOT RUN this notebook from start to finish.  The code 
cells are not designed to be run from the top down but are somewhat 
random stuff I added and modified as needed.   
